## At a Glance

**What's working:** You've developed a strong instinct for using Claude on complex, multi-step workflows — your OmegA repo finalization session (eval suites, paper corrections, runtime package, cleanup, and push) was a great example of orchestrating a full release pipeline in one go. You also showed real sophistication by having Claude build a custom MCP server to extend its own capabilities, and you're good at combining pragmatic tasks like disk cleanup with knowledge preservation. See _Impressive Things You Did_.

**What's hindering you:** On Claude's side, it repeatedly locked onto the wrong root cause before finding the real issue — like chasing a DATABASE_URL fix when the actual blocker was an auth wall — which burns time and trust. On your side, a significant chunk of your sessions were cut short or completely blocked by rate limits and credit exhaustion, and some automation tasks hit environment/permission issues that Claude didn't anticipate because it lacked context about your setup. See _Where Things Go Wrong_.

**Quick wins to try:** Try **custom slash commands** (`/commands`) for your recurring workflows like CLAUDE.md generation or repo finalization checklists — you've done these multiple times and they'd benefit from a reusable template. Also consider **headless mode** to batch predictable tasks (like disk analysis or archive extraction) into scripted runs that don't require you to sit and wait through rate-limit-prone interactive sessions. See _Features to Try_.

**Ambitious workflows:** As models get more capable, you'll be able to spawn parallel sub-agents for your repo finalization work — one handling eval suites, another doing paper corrections, another on cleanup — instead of running them sequentially and risking context limits. Also watch for checkpoint-and-resume workflows that save progress locally after each major step, so when rate limits hit, the next session picks up exactly where you left off instead of losing everything. See _On the Horizon_.

